;orthodoxy.&quot; On the other hand, he is perhaps most famous as the one who advocated that the Bible is not the Word of God &quot;until I encounter it, and it <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>becomes</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the Word of God.&quot; Thus, he is perceived as one who did not embrace traditional orthodoxy. He is considered then the source of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>neo-orthodoxy</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - having some elements of traditional orthodox Christianity (not a denomination, but theology) and yet not accepting the underlying premise of orthodox Christinity concerning the Word of God.<br>
<br>
I have a couple of references that I will dig out that put his theology into perspective. <p>In Christ,<br>
